Barack Obama will be the fourth U.S. president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth American president in history.
The $1.4 million diploma, medal and cheque will be awarded, among other things, for outstanding efforts in strengthening global diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The White House chief and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and have a lot to do.
First, visit the Nobel Institute, where for the first time he will meet the five members of the committee that, in October, elected him from 172 people and 33 organizations.
Afterwards, the presidential couple is scheduled to meet with the King of Norway, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon the visit will culminate with a ceremony in which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive it, though the third to receive it in office.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the award, it will talk about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid this issue, knowing that he is receiving the award as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
Their war efforts increased further with the dispatch of additional troops to Afghanistan, which does not forget to mention any of their critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, diploma and check for ten million Swedish kronor (approximately 24 million Czech kronor).
It proposes to donate them for charitable purposes, but has not yet decided to which organization in particular.
During his full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet attended by the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude toward the award.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling that he didn’t deserve it at all.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents "a challenge to take action."
