Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is funny that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, which he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his eagerly awaited Afghan approach, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only is the phrase “just like in Iraq” used several times in the same text, but he also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush’s January 2007 statement for his own statement: “A New Way Forward.”
It was Bush himself, who three years ago criticized the idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from the civil war, and that criticized it as "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences."
The following months, however, proved that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so that today there is no talk of Iraq in the news.
Bush’s reputation did not improve, however objectively he left his successor in a much more favorable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama is hoping for a repeat of the miracle.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal. He, even despite the traditional subordinate relations, subjected the indecisive riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men to be able to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn’t think of anything better, so at least he fooled the general about 10,000 servicemen.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of Obama’s whole strategy seems to be his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to finish this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq’s society is relatively well organized, its leaders respecting the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is being reached.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are accustomed to changing the chief every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a village of Potemkin, after which patriarchal tribal relations will remain.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confusing relationships, further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even setting a state that is “actionable,” a minimum goal of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy clashes with his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to explode.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "return home soon", will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date for the withdrawal of troops is sheer irresponsibility, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, and do not want to explain to their constituents, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: to try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to seek the answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive for Barack Obama is the fact that the presidential election is three years away and that is why there is still a long way to go to find another strategy, if this is a total failure.
