The Management Revolution or the End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of employees adhering to "values" determined from above as before it was a question of imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to strategies of conquering the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that have no relation to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R & D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) "requires all parties involved (...) to have a proactive conduct and a forward-looking vision"; it needs on the part of employees a commitment that completely opposes the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the concerns of the company as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls are relatively useful
Will internal opinion polls, such as Orange’s questionnaire among its employees, incite managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Second, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory that American “neurosciences” recently revived, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the “commands” (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a mechanistic management posture, unadapted to today’s world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies involves adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating into any reasoning or business management practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make part of their dreams, ambitions and projects a reality.
Today, only studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of mobilization factors, company managers can monitor, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resource management "in place".
In this way, they create a favorable terrain for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo speech: Obama receives praise from the right for ‘just war’
On Friday, the American right, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize has defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States, hailed the speech that Obama had delivered on Thursday.
