The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa hablae looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-meter-long, five-foot-tall animal that ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this wouldn’t have been anything special.
But Tawa trollae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's journal Science.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangaea at the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, spread, and characteristics of early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we’ve found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day — this is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member at the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they gathered in total the remains of five specimens.
A find confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi Indian sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: “Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found.”
Other dinosaur experts don’t share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when the saurians split into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadrupedal sauropods known as "long-necked" and their relatives, and the Stenithischia herbivores.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa trollae is a primitive theropod.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, Nesbitt says.
For example, in Tawa’s skull, the researchers found evidence of air pockets, such as those also possessed by theropod descendants, birds.
Thanks to air pockets, birds’ breathing is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa trovae also the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air pockets, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of later giant sauropods also possessed air pockets and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers deduce that saurians first emerged there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lineages separated at first and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single landmass, the supercontinent Pangaea.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawae the remains of two other theropods not closely related.
The three cannot descend from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We think there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are opponents too.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group to the dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
Their opinion could give a distorted picture, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
While in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and many new species developed, while the kinship became extinct at the Triassic boundary towards the Jurassic.
The success stories were not eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, comments Martin Sander.
A mass extinction may have occurred that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Success stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact halted the rise of a group of species, which had also already evolved in the Triassic and since then led a miserable existence: mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
