In the waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
It is not only in the case of the mentally ill and drug addicts that the boundaries between imagination and reality are blurred.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can unfettered surrender to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, one who experiences sleep-like states during wakefulness, or sees and hears things that others do not see and hear, is most often considered in the modern Western world as crazy or drug addicted, or at least manic.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in drug addicts.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, sometimes blur the boundaries between dream, madness and reality.
Dream-modified states of alert consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although triggers and effects can be distinguished, similar processes can be traced back to the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, states of shamanic possession, and psychoses and hallucinations.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of the neuronal communication substances in the brain – especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine – has been derailed and the interaction between various parts of it is disturbed.
During a schizophrenic psychosis very often appear complex hallucinations and crazed thoughts.
Gravity no longer has power over it.
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and doctors since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived of hallucinations as a form of waking sleep, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness with dream states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all these nonsense, crazy formations, and"
