He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and disappear.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When he is in class he can sometimes not follow the lesson because the teacher – in his eyes and ears – is presenting a new partner, while for the rest he explains in a visible and audible way the mathematical equations.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
As she waits in the dark room for sleep, which often comes late and is scarce, she can’t tell whether she’s awake or dreaming, whether the images she sees, the grimaces or the girl with bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, appear in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, he screams at the figures.
Her parents and friends haven't heard from her, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed selectivity last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations disappeared.
Ever since you've come into contact over the Internet with psychologist Kasten, you know you're not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art out of desperation.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers a restriction of stimuli, it is very likely that after a while they begin to have hallucinations.
I believe that the brain is unoccupied and is responsible for seeking entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, had a small fear of other children and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he learned that the man he’s called dad since he’s had reason isn’t his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, those affected like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain produces, which is why they seem so real.”
Kasten also classifies nocturnal fantasies as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, psychically healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends his patients to appreciate their hallucinations as a special skill.
Boundary between sleep and hallucination
In this overly conscious world, imaginary experiences are usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, a professor at Heidelberg and chief physician of the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in D<0xC3><0xBC>sseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful illness but it also involves something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated so-called Oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as if it were a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that subsequently can not differentiate from being awake.
Oneiric conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while being fully conscious. die bei vollem Bewusstsein eine motorische L<0xC3><0xA4>hmung erleben.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of self or of the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with an own and imaginary world that is decoupled from reality.
A form of borderline situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a change of world occurs, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an unbearable situation in itself that our own creative capacity allows us not to sink into the nothingness of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a soul-saving action.
He was 49 years old, when his consciousness embarked on multi-day trips after heart valve surgery with heart transplantation included, while his body was condemned to immobility in the intensive care station.
Claussen immersed himself in a world created by himself and visited strange places of other times: he found himself prostrate in bed, an older man on board a sanatorium on a train, a robot watching over his health.
It was seen in the early Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek man on a motorcycle kidnapped him in his home country, surfed on his hospital bed in the Alps with firn snow and ran into a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so describe your experience.
On the contrary, the memories of mental journeys are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
Even clearer and more intensive than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our everyday experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations and drug use show how fragile the inner reproduction of external reality is, even when we are awake.
Each modification of the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
