75% of working mothers have had work problems due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fecundity and work history of women in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey conducted among 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about it: 75% of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to motherhood.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of living together as a couple and the number of children, depending on whether or not they work and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unstable job, start living together as a couple, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
"Women between 35 and 49 years old with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting living together, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time from their life trajectory to get them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on motherhood, but less on the timing of the pairing," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they get married and when they have the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the higher the age at which they marry and have their first child.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education were first-time mothers at 25.1 and 32.1 on average, respectively.
"Another division is also established among women according to their level of education.
While those with elementary studies get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those of medium or higher levels invest this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a condition prior to marriage and the arrival of a child, "details Delgado.
