Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As with ABS anti-lock braking and ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all passenger cars and light commercial vehicles of new registration, while for the rest a grace period is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, due to its way of working, it can also help avoid many collisions by range.
The emergency braking assistant increases the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver’s stomp.
But he doesn’t always maintain that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the manufacturer of components for cars Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not come to step on the brake before the collision and half of them did not take advantage of all the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, demands the maximum from the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater – it is estimated that one in four claims with damage to people would be avoided – when the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to slightly acting on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is unavoidable, the device exerts maximum effort to the brakes to minimize damage.
