New tools to test cars
In these days of storms and accidents, not only car workshops win.
Every day thousands of cars that have suffered a loss are towed to a workshop, where an expert must assess the damage suffered and what the cost of repair will be.
No claim is the same, and calculating parts costs and labor time can be a long and complicated task.
The cost of a repair of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including parts and labor, can take two or three hours.
Instead, with the support of the latest computer tools it would be a matter of minutes
That is why almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
Service providers and solutions for claims assessment and maintenance are dedicated to collecting the information supplied to them by manufacturers, and then elaborate it and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the American group Solera, is the leading firm; 80% of the valuations are made with its products.
The other firms that compete in the field of valuation tools and elaboration of information on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
The work with the data supplied by the manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, in Spain they work with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with the information in different formats.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, to the point that in the last five years more versions, variants and engines have been released than in the previous fifteen.
As soon as a new car comes on the market, these companies get to work.
It is a very arduous task, because you have to catalog each of the thousands of parts of the vehicle and enter its price.
In addition, each model is made a "smart" graphic image where you can "prick" different parts of tourism.
If it’s a massive window model, the job can be ready in a week if the process goes too fast.
If it is a minority car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of the cars that are marketed in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models have information about Porsche, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini, for example.
As for the mobile fleet that circulates, they exceed 99%.
To carry out the work of documentation and the elaboration of the databases, Audatex has eight centers spread around the world (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them is specialized in specific brands.
The national headquarters is in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in developing these databases.
2.5 million pieces of data are included each month, and customers receive updates every other day.
The development of this enormous flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and offer various products.
The most frequent use is focused on repair and maintenance, but depending on which countries there are also tools for management of scrapping parts or to calculate the venal or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used vehicles in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer it in our country, but in the United States.
In view of the products offered by Audatex it is easy to get an idea of the type of support they can provide to professionals in the sector.
This company offers ten different tools, being the flagship product AudaPlus, the standard claim assessment solution, aimed at experts.
It includes cars, motorcycles and light or heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the paint scales.
This tool is paid according to use, for each valuation.
The highest cost is 5.75 euros, for customers who use it little, a maximum of ten times a month.
Then each insurance company, which carries out thousands of appraisals, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the total identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it left the assembly line only with its frame number.
AudaGlass focuses on the moons of vehicles, and AudaSubastas is a service open to the professional sector on the internet that allows bidding for vehicles declared total loss.
Its statistics service is very useful to identify trends, perform geodemographic analysis or know the deviations by brands or models.
You can study, for example, how many models of a certain brand have passed through the workshop because of breakdowns or how many have suffered serious accidents in a certain period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tools.
It markets, among others, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for experts and also provides digital images, access to parts or prices and official times of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is an Einsa Group company founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdowns or maintenance of the automobile.
The Gt Appraisal Guide is your historical reference product in the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Its turnover has grown at a rate of 20% per year in the last three years, and in 2008 they invoiced 10.8 million euros.
At the beginning of last year they began their internationalization process, with the installation of an office in Paris.
Audatex was born in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the company’s sources, 62% of its business is generated in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38%, in North and South America. They work with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, 3,000 of them in Spain.
Solera Group’s worldwide turnover (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) will reach $557 million, 3.3% more than in 2008.
In our country the company will enter 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera group was worth $1 billion on the stock exchange, and now its shares are listed for a total value of $2.4 billion.
It has been listed on the New York Stock Exchange since 2007 and is included in the Standard & Poor's benchmark index.
Online auction of damaged cars
Last October the Solera group bought Autoonline, an online platform for the sale of cars such as motorcycles or special vehicles.
The operation involved a disbursement of 59.5 million euros for 85% of the company’s capital, which could be extended next year to the remaining 15%.
The objective of the acquisition was to offer more value-added services to its customers, with the possibility of accessing an immense international market.
This valuation and sales service is aimed exclusively at professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, workshops, scrappers and professional sellers who must register before starting operations.
This platform was created in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650,000 operations across Europe, 500,000 of them in Germany.
Among its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
The website currently has more than 1,500 registered sellers and 4,000 experts.
3,000 ads are managed daily and in the Spanish market about 100 new ads are included every day.
According to Spanish law, a car whose chassis number has been decommissioned cannot be re-circulated, but certain parts that are not damaged can be used as spare parts.
Cars with historical value can be discharged even if they have been discharged after a long process.
Workshop budget in four steps
With the Auda-Taller tool, the Audatex company guarantees that the user obtains a quote in just four steps: identify the vehicle, look for the spare part, create a quote and generate a quote.
Ease of use is an essential condition for these systems, especially to convince older professionals, who to a greater or lesser extent are usually more reluctant to use new management techniques.
The database includes 1,034 vehicles, which are 666 cars, 109 SUVs, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Of course, to use it you need a computer with an internet connection.
Once the model to be repaired is identified by its frame number, an actual graphic image of the model in question appears, and then the necessary spare part is selected.
The user can include variables such as the price of labor, surcharges or discounts, and then can print the budget to deliver to the customer.
AudaTaller is not a valuation tool like AudaPlus, but rather a catalog of references.
The main difference between the two systems is that the workshop-oriented one does not include estimated labor times.
The cost of using this tool for the workshop is 350 euros per year, which the client can finance.
Currently the company Audatex is working to make these images three-dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics see with very good eyes, since it will allow, for example, to select a door and turn it around to see the inner face.
